{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e1834ba-a1db-4b6a-80f0-6e63440aa55f","content":"## What's happening\n\nEach .NET major version has been **raising the x86-64 baseline instruction set** required by the runtime/JIT:\n\n| .NET version | x86-64 baseline | Key additions |\n|---|---|---|\n| ≤ 8 | **x86-64-v1** | SSE, SSE2 (original AMD64 minimum) |\n| 9 | **x86-64-v2** | SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT |\n| 11 | **x86-64-v3** | AVX, AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, FMA, MOVBE, LZCNT |\n\nYour 2012-era CPUs are likely **Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge**. These have AVX but **lack AVX2, BMI1/2, and FMA**, which were introduced with **Haswell in 2013**. The runtime detects the missing v3 instructions at startup and refuses to run.\n\n## Why your other targets are fine\n\n- **Surface Pro X (SQ1 / ARMv8.2):** ARM64 baseline requirements haven't jumped as aggressively; ARMv8.0 base features are still sufficient.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Cortex-A72 / ARMv8.0):** Same — still meets the ARM64 baseline.\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Retire the pre-Haswell nodes** — any x86-64 CPU from 2014+ should have AVX2.\n2. **Stay on .NET 10 (LTS)** for those specific nodes — it's supported through November 2028.\n3. **Check the runtime knob** `DOTNET_EnableSSE3_4=0` — some .NET versions offered environment-variable opt-outs to fall back to a lower baseline, but v3 features are increasingly hard-wired into the JIT; test thoroughly if you try this.\n4. **Use `lscpu` or `cat /proc/cpuinfo`** on the failing node to confirm exactly which flags are missing — look for `avx2`, `bmi1`, `bmi2`, `fma` in the `flags` line.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"108e45e6-4b44-464a-abb3-f975bbff19e1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets when upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements changes.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nStarting with .NET 9 (and continuing), Microsoft 